Our experience was alright. My husband and I lived in Oklahoma and love a good bbq place, so it’s hard to measure up. We ordered takeout and spent about $35 on a brisket sandwich, a burnt ends sandwich and a half rack of ribs. Each dish came with 2 containers of bbq sauce so we got all different sauces. We didn’t love any of the sauces. The burnt ends were actually quite yummy, but we felt it was a little ridiculous that there were only 7 or so little pieces on a sandwich that cost so much. The brisket was tender, but not juicy and no smoke ring. It looked dry but didn’t taste really dry. Again, just not worth the price on a small sandwich. The ribs were tender and pretty decent tasting if we added salt. Again, pricy for what we got.  One thing that we thought was strange for a bbq place is that they don’t sell any meat besides ribs outside of a sandwich. We would actually go back for burnt ends if they sold it by the pound. Overall, the place was alright, but way too pricy for what you get.

I don't understand how there's even 1 bad review, this place was awesome. I've been smoking meat for close to 2 years, and in that time I've tried and been disappointed by every "high end" bbq joint I could find as it just wasn't as good as homemade. Pop's BBQ is the first place that I've found where I was genuinely impressed by the food, and the customer service may be the best I've had anywhere. And it is by no means "expensive" for a bbq joint, it's cheaper than you'll find at another place and the other's have lower quality food. We'll be back any time we're in the Iowa City area, I'd give more stars if I could. We had the ribs, wings, mac and cheese (a must-try,) and a pulled pork sandwich. All were great.

Good food, EXTREMELY poor catering service, and unprofessional management.  We chose Pop's to cater our wedding because we love the food there. In spite of our guest's rave reviews about the food (for just a lunch or casual dinner this place is awesome), the catering service left a LOT to be desired. Eric, the owner, was difficult to work with, rude, and we never did receive the requested copy of their certificate of liability insurance, which was required by our venue.  We chose our menu and placed our deposit for our food in January 2017 for a June 2017 wedding. We were quoted $2000 for 130 people with a 10% deposit up front to reserve our spot. When we asked for a copy of the contract we received a photo copied order form with poorly written out instructions for what we had ordered. I had to fill in all the information for our venue, date, etc. even though the person I talked to on the phone (Eric, the owner) said he had taken all the information down. Our requests for a more formal contract were ignored. We thought it was a small thing and didn't think much of it until halfway through March when we received a call from Eric saying he had lost our "contract" and couldn't remember what we had ordered, what our date was, and whether we had paid our deposit. Again, we got things straightened out, but I was beginning to get worried. It was also during this phone call that Eric told me we were being "way undercharged" but that he was going to "let it slide" since he had had some staff turnover since we placed our initial order (according to the catering prices posted online we were charged correctly).  When we contacted Pop's again at the end of May, 30 days out from our wedding, Eric was still shaky on the details but seemed to have things mostly in order. That is, until the week of our wedding when my fiance called to do our final confirmation... First, Eric had again misplaced our catering "contract" and had no idea when or where the wedding was, what time he needed to arrive, or what he needed to bring. He attempted to confirm back our order to us only to find he had mixed us up with another event the same day. He also asked if he could serve HyVee potato salad instead of his own recipe (why would we pay $2k to be served grocery store food?). He complained about our venue to my fiance, and then asked to show up to set up half an hour before dinner was to be served at our reception.  The service only got worse on our wedding day. Eric sent his mother out while we were setting up to tell us that she and her husband would be at our venue at 4:00 on the day of to set up, and that Eric would be coming with the food later. We reiterated to her that we required all vendors to be completely set up before the ceremony began, and she assured me they would be. Come the day of there was no sign of anyone from Pop's at 4:00. Instead they showed up in the middle of our outdoor ceremony, distracting our guests from the service. They were still setting up when dinner began at 6:00, and Eric snapped at my bridesmaids saying "you need to fix this mess" when he had issues with the electrical plugs ins (we asked him to bring extension cords and power strips, but he didn't). Our DJ ended up having to unplug all his equipment so Pop's could power their food warmers, which left us with just a Bluetooth speaker to play music during dinner. We even had guests running around with extension cords trying to get the Pop's crew up and running, instead of enjoying the cocktail hour.  Overall we were really looking forward to supporting one of our favorite mom and pop eateries, but the constant headaches made it barely worth it. When we called Eric to discuss our experience after the wedding he was defensive and rude, and dismissive of our concerns. Our guests very much enjoyed the food but I think we will be taking our business elsewhere in the future.

My wife and I stopped in for lunch on a Saturday. She had a chicken sandwich, I had a brisket sandwich, and we had corn bread and cole slaw.  I'm not sure where they get the idea of bbq... Her chicken was very dry and tasted like someone had tossed it into smoke for a few minutes to give it a "smoked" flavor.  My brisket wasn't much different.  The corn bread tasted more like cake than corn bread (next time, try reading a corn bread recipe from a corn meal box and it'd be worlds better)... The slaw was bitter at best...  And for the privilege of eating this we paid more than $25...  Next time I want bbq I'll go to a place local to us where you can actually SMELL the smoke before you go in... Though I didn't even smell smoke in this place.... Should have figured when I got no smoke smell around them...  Ah well, live and learn...

Good Stuff

I was a big fan of The Pit which was previously in this location, but after a few trips to Pop's, I like it even more than I liked The Pit.  I'm not entirely sure why there aren't more people there each time I go (poor location maybe?), but I'll take it, less waiting time for me.  I've been to Pop's a couple of times per month since it opened.  Pros: unique menu with lots of options (including harb/garlic fries -- yum!), usually fresh and quite flavorful, oftentimes there's plenty of room in there to sit, my favorite brisket in Iowa City, and the chicken isn't bad either  Cons: sometimes takes an unusually long time to get food (10 mins for 1 sandwich?), they got rid of their turkey (perhaps not a good seller?), friend got ribs once and they were rubbery as if they had been made that afternoon and microwaved when we got there

This is by far the best BBQ place in Iowa City. With all the new BBQ places popping up, you might be inclined to try them, but waste not your time, or your taste buds, and feast on the yumminess othat Pop's has to offer! Eeeeevvvvveeerrrryyyyything is good there!
